text.paragraph:
Excessively large dosages of antihistamines, including promethazine HCl tablets in pediatric patients may cause sudden death (see 



                              OVERDOSAGE
                           ). Hallucinations and convulsions have occurred with therapeutic doses and overdoses of promethazine HCl in pediatric patients. In pediatric patients who are acutely ill associated with dehydration, there is an increased susceptibility to dystonias with the use of promethazine HCl.

Asthma, nasal stuffiness, respiratory depression (potentially fatal) and apnea (potentially fatal). (See 



                              WARNINGS: Respiratory Depression.


  )

Angioneurotic edema. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome (potentially fatal) has also been reported. (See 



                              WARNINGS: Neuroleptic Malignant Syndrome.


  )

Antiemetics should not be used in vomiting of unknown etiology in children and adolescents (see 



                              WARNINGS: Use in Pediatric Patients
                           ).
